Single-cell RNA-seq analysis example

This analysis of single-cell RNA-seq data contains several questionable decisions in the processing and analysis. Which parts of this analysis would you have done differently, and why?

The paper presenting this data can be accessed at https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-020-14457-z.

# load some libraries we will need later
library(Rtsne)
library(C50)

# set a random seed for reproducibility
set.seed(1234)

# load the raw data - rows are genes, columns are cells
cts = readRDS('cuomo-raw-matrix.rds')

# how does data look?
dim(cts)
## [1] 3557 1880
cts[1:5,1:5]
##                 21241_6_104 21241_6_117 21241_6_122 21241_6_131 21241_6_133
## ENSG00000075624        2264        5111        6071        5823        6566
## ENSG00000147869        4677         419        2056        3106         229
## ENSG00000184009        1365        3698        4089        2692        3957
## ENSG00000111640         579        1064         684         952         610
## ENSG00000067225        1252         110         578         991         731
# so we have data for the expression of 3557 genes in 1880 cells
# next, we load some metadata
meta = readRDS('cuomo-meta-example.rds')
head(meta)
##             donor  day
## 21241_6_104  hayt day3
## 21241_6_117  <NA> day3
## 21241_6_122  hayt day3
## 21241_6_131  hayt day3
## 21241_6_133  <NA> day3
## 21241_6_147  <NA> day3
# visualize cells on PCA
# we have to take transpose of count matrix since prcomp expects features as columns, not rows
pca.res = prcomp(t(cts))$x
plot(pca.res[,1], pca.res[,2])

# also look at t-SNE
tsne.res = Rtsne(t(cts))$Y
plot(tsne.res[,1], tsne.res[,2])

# next, we cluster the data with k-means and visualize on PCA and t-SNE
kmeans.clustering = kmeans(t(cts), center=11, iter.max=10, nstart=1)$cluster
plot(pca.res[,1], pca.res[,2], col=kmeans.clustering)

plot(tsne.res[,1], tsne.res[,2], col=kmeans.clustering)

# Unfortunately, we have lost the information on which donor half the cells came from! We will need to train a machine learning model to predict the donor of the cells based on their gene expression.
summary(meta)
##   donor       day     
##  hayt:219   day0:383  
##  melw:164   day1:423  
##  naah:167   day2:435  
##  pahc:148   day3:639  
##  qunz:138             
##  vils: 94             
##  NA's:950
plot(tsne.res[,1], tsne.res[,2], col=meta$donor)

missing.donor.mask = is.na(meta$donor)

# we train a decision tree on the data
donor.dt = C5.0(t(cts), meta$donor, subset=!missing.donor.mask, trials=1)
donor.dt
## 
## Call:
## C5.0.default(x = t(cts), y = meta$donor, trials = 1, subset = !missing.donor.mask)
## 
## Classification Tree
## Number of samples: 1880 
## Number of predictors: 3557 
## 
## Tree size: 39 
## 
## Non-standard options: attempt to group attributes
# how does it predict the donor of the remaining cells?
dt.predictions = predict(donor.dt, t(cts[,missing.donor.mask]))
summary(dt.predictions)
## hayt melw naah pahc qunz vils 
##  193  152  172  153  188   92
